<subSubSection id="4FF0F1E8FFEFFFA5A7ADFC1FFEDCD8A7" pageId="118" pageNumber="119" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="0755A263FFEFFFA5A7ADFC1FFEF0D80B" blockId="118.[189,310,1008,1034]" box="[189,310,1008,1034]" pageId="118" pageNumber="119">
<heading id="5C1D150FFFEFFFA5A7ADFC1FFEF0D80B" bold="true" box="[189,310,1008,1034]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="118" pageNumber="119" reason="3">
<emphasis id="359E7E71FFEFFFA5A7ADFC1FFEF0D80B" bold="true" box="[189,310,1008,1034]" pageId="118" pageNumber="119">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0755A263FFEFFFA5A7ADFBCFFEDCD8A7" blockId="118.[188,1400,1056,1190]" pageId="118" pageNumber="119">
This species may be separated from other 
<taxonomicName id="C0EAD9E0FFEFFFA5A5B5FBCFFCD4D83B" authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1892" box="[677,786,1056,1082]" class="Arachnida" family="Charinidae" genus="Charinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amblypygi" pageId="118" pageNumber="119" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="359E7E71FFEFFFA5A5B5FBCFFCD4D83B" box="[677,786,1056,1082]" italics="true" pageId="118" pageNumber="119">Charinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in eastern South America by means of the following combination of characters: tegument covered with clavate setae; carapace and legs dark in color; leg I tarsus I with 23–28 articles with length of first tarsal article equal to combined length of subsequent ten articles.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="4FF0F1E8FFEFFFA5A7ADFB20FCE1D93D" pageId="118" pageNumber="119" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="0755A263FFEFFFA5A7ADFB20FE82D8E8" blockId="118.[189,324,1231,1257]" box="[189,324,1231,1257]" pageId="118" pageNumber="119">
<heading id="5C1D150FFFEFFFA5A7ADFB20FE82D8E8" bold="true" box="[189,324,1231,1257]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="118" pageNumber="119" reason="3">
<emphasis id="359E7E71FFEFFFA5A7ADFB20FE82D8E8" bold="true" box="[189,324,1231,1257]" pageId="118" pageNumber="119">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0755A263FFEFFFA5A7ADFB11FCE1D93D" blockId="118.[189,1399,1278,1341]" pageId="118" pageNumber="119">Although unspecified by the author, the name is a Latin adjective meaning ‘of mountains’, which refers to the occurrence of this species in a hilly landscape.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
